  1. Fusion beats: sinus and ventricular beat occur simultaneously (QRS morphology is intermediate VT beat and sinus beat)

[!INFO] Mnemonic: ABCDE

  1. Axis will be north-west (-90 to 180)
  2. Broad complexes
  3. Presence of Condordance (see Concordance above)
  4. D - dissociation (AV) (Fusion beats and capture beats are a sign of dissociation)
  5. E - Early part of QRS
  • Because VT depolarizations are initially conducted through the ventricular muscle (and then reach the conducting system), the initial part of QRS complex will be 'slow' -> i.e slurred.

Syphilis

  • Dorsal nucleus of the vagus nerve is a mixed visceral afferent and efferent nucleus.
    • It supplies the gut upto the distal transverse colong (midgut / hindgut junction)
  • Nucleus ambiguus -> supplies efferent fibers to striated muscle of the pharynx and larynx.

"The posterior column degeneration accounts for the loss of position and vibration senses and the sensory ataxia. The loss of large neurons in the sensory ganglia causes extinction of tendon reflexes" - Source - Medscape

  • Requires systemic antifungal therapy because topical do not penetrate the hair shaft.

Pytiriasis versicolor

  • Myxoedema coma: Presents with low BP, bradycardia, and hypothermia. (Managed with levothyroxine as well as hydrocortisone for presumed concomitant hypoadrenalism. Replace corticosteroid first, or there is risk of worsening symptoms. )

Q 9 : Diabetic ketoacidosis

- **Urinary ketones are not reliable as a indicator of resolution** as they can persist after DKA resolution. 

- **Loss of reflexes** (*lower motor sign*) with **up-going Babinski reflex**. (*upper motor sign*) (Mnemonic: Spinal tract demyelination causes UMN signs, peripheral neuropathy causes LMN signs)

[!TIP] Mnemonics:

  • Nucleus of tractus solitarius is a sensory nucleus. (NTS - The S is for sensory)
    • "Nucleus of tractus sensarious"
    • Receives afferents from the vagal nerve and tongue
  • Nucleus ambiguus is a motor nucleus which contains motor efferents to
    • muscles of the soft palate and larynx and parasympathetic motor neurons to the heart.
      Source

They secrete many inflammatory mediators (histamine, prostaglandins, leukotrienes) when activated by a antigen which crosslinks the mast cell receptors which are membrane bound IgE.

Linezolid

  • Similar spectrum to vancomycin.
  • Used when there is vancomycin resistance.
    [Source](Linezolid: a review of its properties, function, and use in critical care - PMC)

Testing 1,2,3

  • Cup : Disk ratio > 0.7 is seen.
  • Managementof AACG - acetazolamide 500mg stat followed by pilocarpine (muscarinic agonist)
  • POAG - primary open angle glaucoma - associated with myopia (long eye ball) and not hypermetropia (short eye ball) like AACG.
    • 360° selective laser trabeculoplasty (SLT) first-line to people with an IOP of ≥ 24 mmHg
    • Latanoprost (prostaglandin analogue) is a first line drug in POAG. It increases uveroscleral outflow.
    • Timolol (beta blocker) reduces production of aqueous humour. Second line drug.
    • Last line: Surgical trabeculoplasty
    • There is partial or total loss of neurons of the ciliary ganglion. (and also loss of some spinal neurons)

Mastocytosis

[!TIP] Mnemonic: A bit like carcinoid syndrome (flushing, diarrhoea) but mastocytosis has a rash.

  • Abnormal accumulation of mast cells in tissues.
  • Cutaneous mastocytosis - more in children.
    • Characteristic rash : urticaria pigmentosa. (aka Maculopapular cutaneous mastocytosis)
    • Blistering is seen exclusively in children.
    • Doesn't require specific treatment settles by teen years.
    • However, predisposes to anaphylaxis with insect stings and severe reactions can cause fainting.
  • Systemic mastocytosis - more in adults.
    • Mast cells accumulate in spleen, liver, bone marrow, lymphatics.
    • Symptoms: flushing, headache, dyspnea, wheezing, rhinorrhea, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, and syncope.
    • #hepatosplenomegaly
  • Diagnosis:
    • Urinary histamine levels
    • Serum tryptase (is not elevated in pure cutaneous mastocytosis) but is elevated in systemic mastocysosis.
